    <section id="philosophy" class="py-14 border-b border-border scroll-mt-16 print:hidden" aria-labelledby="philosophy-heading">
      <h2 id="philosophy-heading" class="flex items-center gap-2 text-xl sm:text-2xl font-bold mb-3">
        <span class="w-2 h-2 rounded-full bg-accent shrink-0"></span> How I Approach Engineering
      </h2>
      <p class="max-w-2xl text-text-secondary mb-8">A few things that shape how I design and build systems — all visible in the projects above.</p>

      <div class="grid sm:grid-cols-3 gap-7">
        <div>
          <p class="font-bold mb-1.5">Simplicity over cleverness</p>
          <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary">I default to the boring, well-understood solution and only reach for complexity when the problem actually demands it. Code that's easy to delete is easier to maintain than code that's clever.</p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <p class="font-bold mb-1.5">Design for failure, not just the happy path</p>
          <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary">Dropped connections and stale state aren't edge cases — they're normal operating conditions for real users, which is why I build offline-first and let systems degrade gracefully by default.</p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <p class="font-bold mb-1.5">Automate the repeatable</p>
          <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary">Linting, formatting, compliance reports, pre-commit gates — anything a human shouldn't have to remember by hand gets automated, so review time goes to logic instead of style.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
